			<ns0:name>kschi...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/108470876877739532758/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">This would not be that hard to add to the x86-64 validator. We currently use an operand flag corresponding to zero-extend from 32-bits to 64-bits, to verify the top 32 bits are zero. All we need to do is mark the instructions that sign extend from 32-bits to 64-bits, and then allow either flag to be used as the acceptance criteria.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2010-07-13T14:55:54.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2010-07-13T14:55:54.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates /><ns0:title>Comment 1 by kschi...@google.com</ns0:title><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=689#c1" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/689/comments/full/1" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /></ns0:entry>